<p>First of all, I have nothing against Elb... Just used him as an example to outline the problem that I have been having with loot.  Every time I ask disco for advice, there is dead silence it seems.  I don't want to keep track of everything that someone has won and try to determine if they should get a roll or not.<br />
<br />
Bem, I guess I am not comfortable with whatever the "guild-guidelines" are.  I really don't mind how YOU do loot, but I am not you and thus unless you can explain exaclty what you do, I wont be able to emulate you.  Frankly, I feel you decide on the fly on a case by case basis, and you would problably handle each case differently than I.  There are some very broad guidelines, but they are not enough to bolster my confidence.<br />
<br />
And Bustyn, for every question you raise on any point system, I can raise 2 more with how awarded loot is assigned or how people are hand picked to /random.  How much is raid attendence a factor?  How much is being a hydra a factor?  How much is level and class a factor?  How do you choose (like in the case of the chain BP we got) who gets something when BOTH or multiple people deserve it?  What if someone has already won today, or the last time we killed Lodi?<br />
<br />
As far as my proposed system, the /rand thing is to establish an initial loot order.  When something drops, people on the top have first rights if they wish to loot.  I *still* think certain things like breastplates, post epic weapons, and similar mega-items be awarded.<br />
<br />
Anyway... the point is I do not feel confident or competent awarding loot.  Perhaps the true solution is that I refrain from being involved in it.  Sure I will offer my viewpoint when neccesary, but I will not go as far as deciding who gets what.  I'm saying that because I don't want to across like I am trying to force a change.  I am only trying to say that I am not personally comfortable handling these things under the current system, and offering suggestion on what I feel would help.<br />
<br />
Maybe all we need are some WRITTEN guidelines that we can all look over?  I think that may put me at rest anyway.</p>

