<font size="2"><b>Venerial</b></font> - <font size="1">7/21/2002 at 06:31 AM</font>
<p>The way my guild does loot (OoP), is IMO one of the best ways, other then a DKP system (too complicated hehe)<br />
<br />
They have a table with each member's name and loot they aquired the whole time they been in the guild. when a loot item drops, an officer with a 2nd computer will check the table list, and see who has the least amount of loot, if the item will be an upgrade for them, and how many raids they attended. The officer then relays the info back to the other officers, and then they vote on who should receive the item in question.<br />
The player with the most votes, obviously gets the item. Once that happens, they put  the item, and the day they got the item in the table list, so that person won't get 2 items in a row (unless it was gonna rot)<br />
Their order of preference is as follows (don;t quote me on this, I could be wrong)<br />
1.) Is it for a main or a twink.<br />
2.) Will it benefit the guild as a whole.<br />
3.) Have they attended a good amount of raids required for the item that dropped.<br />
4.) How long have they been in the guild<br />
5.) How long has it been since they last got a loot drop.<br />
6.) Is the item gonna be used as an upgrade, or a "toy"<br />
<br />
<br />
I'm sure theres more, but thats all I know about their loot policy. Now, you're prolly asking yourself how I know all this, and I'm not even an officer in OoP.<br />
Lets just say I have a lot of good friends in the guild that tell me things =p<br />
<br />
You should also try www.guildboss.com ,<br />
It's guild management software, helps you keep track of things like raid attendance, loot distribution, meetings, etc..  I think it costs like $30, but its well worth the money, and I'm sure if you searched around, you could find a warez version of it =p<br />
<br />
Hope this helps.<br />
